1
00:01:07,920 --> 00:01:14,109
Wait!

2
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:18,358
Stop!

3
00:01:21,440 --> 00:01:23,590
Please wait!

4
00:01:23,880 --> 00:01:29,034
Stop!

5
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:31,393
Is anyone home?

6
00:03:58,760 --> 00:04:01,194
Is there anyone home?

7
00:04:07,040 --> 00:04:09,429
Can I come in?

8
00:04:17,720 --> 00:04:20,473
Please, I am a foreigner.

9
00:04:20,920 --> 00:04:22,114
And I'm lost.

10
00:04:36,320 --> 00:04:38,356
I know someone's there.

11
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:42,309
Hello?

12
00:04:53,840 --> 00:04:55,432
Please, I need help.

13
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:06,358
This is completely new for me, professor.

14
00:07:06,480 --> 00:07:08,516
I simply can't imagine
how a expert on insects...

15
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:10,989
...could be so helpful for the police.

16
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:15,511
Would you please explain that
more detailled.

17
00:07:15,640 --> 00:07:18,438
Of course. You can't see the
connections on first sight.

18
00:07:18,640 --> 00:07:22,428
When I decided to specialize
in animal cadavers, ...

19
00:07:22,520 --> 00:07:24,317
...I did not have the least idea of that.

20
00:07:24,440 --> 00:07:25,634
John, do I really have to listen to that again?

21
00:07:25,720 --> 00:07:29,872
Oh yes, just as you had to
on the first murder case.

22
00:07:30,040 --> 00:07:32,235
You came to me because
you did not know how to go on.

23
00:07:32,360 --> 00:07:35,477
We solved the case together.

24
00:07:35,640 --> 00:07:40,919
When a dead body is exposed to nature
it will be eaten by insects sooner or later.

25
00:07:41,040 --> 00:07:44,510
You naughty girl

26
00:07:47,320 --> 00:07:49,197
Where did you find that?

27
00:07:49,320 --> 00:07:51,754
You could hurt yourself.

28
00:07:51,920 --> 00:07:55,071
It is sharp.

29
00:07:55,240 --> 00:07:58,391
It is not a toy.

30
00:07:58,640 --> 00:08:05,432
Outside?

31
00:08:05,640 --> 00:08:09,872
And who, may I ask, put it out there?

32
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:15,837
Don't you ever play with this again.

33
00:08:21,120 --> 00:08:23,714
I forgot to introduce you... this is Inga.

34
00:08:23,880 --> 00:08:26,314
She's my nurse.

35
00:08:26,440 --> 00:08:30,228
If I pick out something with
my laser she'll bring it to me.

36
00:08:31,880 --> 00:08:35,236
She's also my friend, too.

37
00:08:35,400 --> 00:08:37,470
Aren't you?

38
00:08:37,920 --> 00:08:42,152
But she is a very good nurse.

39
00:08:42,360 --> 00:08:45,318
Cadaver-eating insects are
divided into eight groups.

40
00:08:45,520 --> 00:08:49,274
These eight groups of insects come
to the corpse one after the other.

41
00:08:49,440 --> 00:08:53,797
And this only in certain
moments and at a precise time.

42
00:08:53,960 --> 00:08:56,838
Never sooner and never later.

43
00:08:57,720 --> 00:09:00,154
We call them the eight squadrons of death.

44
00:09:01,160 --> 00:09:05,836
First, the common fly comes to the
rotting corpse and lays its eggs.

45
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:08,831
This is the beginnig of the cycle.

46
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:12,476
Each group of insects stays for exactly fifteen days.

47
00:09:12,640 --> 00:09:15,359
So, you have to multiply fifteen by eight.

48
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:18,709
The number of groups.
This equals four months.

49
00:09:18,920 --> 00:09:23,072
Correct. In this case the cycle seems to be complete.

50
00:09:23,320 --> 00:09:26,710
Yet, it is already in the second generation.

51
00:09:26,920 --> 00:09:32,119
From this we may conclude that
this head is rotting for eight months.

52
00:09:32,320 --> 00:09:35,869
By calculating and determining the number,
the look and the kind of the insects, ...

53
00:09:35,960 --> 00:09:38,315
...you can find out the exact date of death.

54
00:09:38,440 --> 00:09:39,714
or of the murder.

55
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:43,793
So our victim was decapitated
some 8 month ago.

56
00:09:43,960 --> 00:09:45,439
And 15 days.

57
00:09:46,320 --> 00:09:49,790
You must not forget, that the body was on
the bottom of the lake for fifteen days.

58
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:55,916
Before the gases which result from
decomposition brought it to the surface.

59
00:09:56,920 --> 00:09:58,797
Where the first flies were already waiting.

60
00:09:58,960 --> 00:10:00,632
Exactly eight and a half months.

61
00:10:00,920 --> 00:10:05,994
Perhaps less. It was extraordinary warm then.

62
00:10:06,320 --> 00:10:12,714
However, I may assume that the person was
decapitated between the 7th and the 10th.

63
00:10:13,280 --> 00:10:14,395
Is that correct?

64
00:10:15,640 --> 00:10:16,914
Let's think about it.

65
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:21,757
The first girl disappeard on September 9.

66
00:10:21,960 --> 00:10:24,155
A sixteen-year-old tourist from Denmark.

67
00:10:24,320 --> 00:10:27,471
The body was never found.

68
00:10:27,720 --> 00:10:29,870
Same as with the others.

69
00:10:30,480 --> 00:10:31,913
It is not nice.

70
00:10:32,920 --> 00:10:34,194
Like Greta.

71
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:37,269
Poor Greta.

72
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:43,152
She is also on the list.

73
00:10:43,800 --> 00:10:46,234
She is missing but we have
no proof that she is dead.

74
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:49,392
After finding this what's the use
of hiding from the facts.

75
00:10:50,920 --> 00:10:55,072
There is a killer.

76
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:00,234
A vicious killer.

77
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:01,833
We'll get him.

78
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:05,877
Someone has to catch this monster.

79
00:11:07,680 --> 00:11:08,510
Good night, professor.

80
00:11:37,080 --> 00:11:38,991
Do you know this part of the country?

81
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:41,156
No, this is my first trip to europe.

82
00:11:41,320 --> 00:11:45,598
People call it the swiss transylvania.

83
00:11:45,920 --> 00:11:48,480
Why?
- I don't know. They just do.

84
00:11:49,400 --> 00:11:51,914
So, you are the Corvino girl!

85
00:11:52,160 --> 00:11:54,754
You father is terribly...
- Yes, he is.

86
00:11:54,920 --> 00:11:56,911
I admire him very much.

87
00:11:57,120 --> 00:11:58,599
I thought he might have come with you.

88
00:11:58,720 --> 00:12:01,234
No, he is workin on the Philippins.

89
00:12:01,360 --> 00:12:03,078
He'll be there for almost a year.

90
00:12:03,200 --> 00:12:05,760
He can't even be reached by telephone.

91
00:12:06,320 --> 00:12:09,517
Well in any case.
He has placed you in good hands.

92
00:12:09,880 --> 00:12:14,237
You know I'm sure you are
going to like our school.

93
00:12:14,480 --> 00:12:16,630
To begin with, we all speak english.

94
00:12:16,880 --> 00:12:20,156
And the our academic program
is based on the american one.

95
00:12:20,360 --> 00:12:21,873
Ah... a bee...

96
00:12:22,040 --> 00:12:24,679
Be carefull it may sting you.

97
00:12:25,200 --> 00:12:26,315
No!

98
00:12:31,920 --> 00:12:34,354
Leave it alone!

99
00:12:35,560 --> 00:12:36,879
Don't kill her.

100
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:44,918
It won't hurt me.
Insects never hurt me. I love them.

101
00:12:45,920 --> 00:12:47,558
You... you love them?

102
00:12:47,680 --> 00:12:50,353
Yes, I love all insects.

103
00:12:50,920 --> 00:12:53,957
If you mean...

104
00:13:04,920 --> 00:13:14,158
Now Jennifer has arrived.

105
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:17,358
And the first night will come.

106
00:13:17,680 --> 00:13:21,070
A night she'll never forget.

107
00:13:23,920 --> 00:13:25,433
Take her baggage.

108
00:13:31,720 --> 00:13:32,914
It is beautiful, isn't it?

109
00:13:34,920 --> 00:13:37,434
The estate was once Richard Wagner's.

110
00:13:37,720 --> 00:13:39,597
The school is occupied in the main building.

111
00:13:39,720 --> 00:13:41,870
The others are closed because they are not safe.

112
00:13:41,960 --> 00:13:42,790
Never go in there.

113
00:13:42,920 --> 00:13:44,638
Come on.

114
00:14:10,720 --> 00:14:13,075
I'm starved.
You got anythin to eat?

115
00:14:13,200 --> 00:14:14,076
No, sorry.

116
00:14:14,320 --> 00:14:17,869
I haven't eaten for two days now.

117
00:14:18,920 --> 00:14:19,875
What is that?

118
00:14:20,080 --> 00:14:24,437
Baby food.

119
00:14:27,720 --> 00:14:31,679
My parents left it when they
visited me with my little brother.

120
00:14:32,720 --> 00:14:33,948
He's seven months old.

121
00:14:34,120 --> 00:14:37,795
I bet he is the only male who has
ever seen the inside of this place.

122
00:14:38,320 --> 00:14:43,155
Vegetables, how nice. I'm vegetarian.
Do you have a spoon?

123
00:14:43,320 --> 00:14:43,957
No.

124
00:15:02,320 --> 00:15:03,309
How is it?

125
00:15:05,720 --> 00:15:06,755
Like cat food.

126
00:15:06,960 --> 00:15:10,111
By the way, I'm Sophie. I'm French.
- Jenniffer.

127
00:15:10,360 --> 00:15:12,635
Did you see the director already?

128
00:15:12,880 --> 00:15:14,632
If you talk of the devil...

129
00:15:17,120 --> 00:15:21,079
You are the new girl.
You were expected this afternoon.

130
00:15:21,240 --> 00:15:25,313
The flight was delayed.

131
00:15:29,360 --> 00:15:32,875
The school has its rules.
I'm sorry, but I must confiscate this.

132
00:15:33,640 --> 00:15:35,596
Hey wait. You don't know who that is.
That's Paul Corvino.

133
00:15:35,800 --> 00:15:39,873
Sophie that is enough. Get into bed!
And if I catch you smoking again, you'll be sorry.

134
00:15:40,720 --> 00:15:42,312
And you young lady... to bed.

135
00:15:44,880 --> 00:15:46,108
And switch off the light.

136
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:54,068
That bitch stealing Paul Corvino.

137
00:15:54,640 --> 00:15:57,712
It is all right.
I have a bunch of them in the bag.

138
00:15:57,920 --> 00:16:01,469
So tomorrow we put them
all up all over the room.

139
00:16:01,920 --> 00:16:05,390
I've seen all his movies
I saw his last one three times.

140
00:16:05,720 --> 00:16:09,508
Luck for you. He must have made
me zip through it at least 15 times.

141
00:16:09,880 --> 00:16:11,393
He said he trust in my opinon.

142
00:16:11,720 --> 00:16:13,790
You mean you know him?

143
00:16:14,920 --> 00:16:16,319
Yes, of course I do.

144
00:16:16,560 --> 00:16:17,993
Have you been to bed with him?

145
00:16:18,320 --> 00:16:23,394
Paul Corvino is my father.
- Oh, sorry.

146
00:16:23,520 --> 00:16:24,396
It's all right.

147
00:16:25,040 --> 00:16:26,917
I do know everything about you!
- Do you?

148
00:16:27,160 --> 00:16:30,118
Your mother lived in India and owned a hotel.
She was married again.

149
00:16:30,320 --> 00:16:31,036
Not like your father.

150
00:16:31,160 --> 00:16:32,673
You were only 7 when they split up.

151
00:16:33,800 --> 00:16:34,630
No, 8.

152
00:16:34,840 --> 00:16:36,319
You were 7!

153
00:16:36,560 --> 00:16:38,710
How do you know that?

154
00:16:38,920 --> 00:16:41,070
I read Fangoria. - Oh!

155
00:16:42,920 --> 00:16:55,230
It was christmas. I was checking the
presents when the phone rings.

156
00:16:57,160 --> 00:17:01,358
Ma answered.

157
00:17:07,440 --> 00:17:11,399
She said she will come soon.

158
00:17:18,280 --> 00:17:19,554
It was her lover.

159
00:17:22,240 --> 00:17:23,832
Then she went...

160
00:17:27,200 --> 00:17:29,350
...and did never came back.

161
00:17:31,920 --> 00:17:34,434
I always remember it.
Dad got 12 presents.

162
00:17:34,720 --> 00:17:38,952
He said he got the 13. From mother to hurt him.

163
00:17:44,200 --> 00:17:46,191
You didn't read that in Fangoria?

164
00:17:46,320 --> 00:17:48,276
You know I am really glad you are here.

165
00:17:48,440 --> 00:17:50,192
I always had to sleep alone.

166
00:17:50,320 --> 00:17:52,390
It can be very scary.

167
00:17:52,560 --> 00:17:53,913
Thank's for coming.

168
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:56,116
I am the one who should thank you.

169
00:17:56,280 --> 00:17:58,714
Don't let me forget that.
I owe you a meal.

170
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:03,351
You know... there is a murder around here!

171
00:18:03,560 --> 00:18:08,429
A maniac who kidnaps girls all ages and kills them.

172
00:18:09,320 --> 00:18:11,151
Could we change the subject?

173
00:18:11,320 --> 00:18:14,357
I need my sleep.
I'm really tired from the trip.

174
00:18:14,920 --> 00:18:18,595
You're right.
Sometimes I can't sleep all night thinking about it.

175
00:18:19,320 --> 00:18:21,709
What do you think about before you fall asleep?

176
00:18:25,040 --> 00:18:26,109
My father.

177
00:18:27,720 --> 00:18:30,837
If I thought about your father
I'd never get any sleep.

178
00:18:34,840 --> 00:18:37,752
Can I still watch some TV?
I have headphones as well

179
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:41,188
No problem, good night, Sophie.

180
00:18:41,320 --> 00:18:42,309
Sleep well, Jenniffer.

181
00:24:22,200 --> 00:24:26,239
Are you hurt?

182
00:24:53,680 --> 00:24:55,079
What you are doing on the street at night?

183
00:24:58,000 --> 00:24:59,115
Can't you answer?

184
00:25:01,720 --> 00:25:03,199
Why are you dressed like that?

185
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:09,108
Look at her eyes, she used drugs!

186
00:25:32,320 --> 00:25:33,673
Can you see anything?

187
00:25:33,800 --> 00:25:36,598
What are we doing now?

188
00:25:36,720 --> 00:25:38,597
Lets run away.

189
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:33,709
Where are you coming from?

190
00:26:38,920 --> 00:26:40,717
O.k., I'm coming with you.

191
00:27:07,720 --> 00:27:09,915
Is this the first time you've been sleepwalking?

192
00:27:10,920 --> 00:27:13,559
No.

193
00:27:14,920 --> 00:27:19,550
Do you know what happened?

194
00:27:24,400 --> 00:27:29,838
I can't remember anything.

195
00:27:34,800 --> 00:27:36,313
My savior.

196
00:27:36,560 --> 00:27:38,198
Are you american?

197
00:27:38,440 --> 00:27:39,953
I am studying at the academy.

198
00:27:40,120 --> 00:27:41,155
Where are you from?

199
00:27:41,720 --> 00:27:45,633
I am from Scotland.
I came here as student and stayed to teach.

200
00:27:46,320 --> 00:27:48,311
Then I had this accident.

201
00:27:48,720 --> 00:27:50,597
I haven't moved since.

202
00:27:50,760 --> 00:27:52,034
What do you teach?

203
00:27:52,280 --> 00:27:56,034
Enthomology.
Study insects.

204
00:27:56,520 --> 00:27:57,270
Really?

205
00:27:57,520 --> 00:27:59,112
Do insects interest you?

206
00:27:59,400 --> 00:28:01,994
Yeah. A lot!
I love them.

207
00:28:02,160 --> 00:28:02,910
You mean that?

208
00:28:03,560 --> 00:28:05,790
Absolutely! Why?

209
00:28:06,320 --> 00:28:11,792
You remind me of another girl.
Greta.

210
00:28:12,120 --> 00:28:15,157
Used to come here somtimes and help out.
Mostly secretarial work. And then...

211
00:28:15,520 --> 00:28:16,430
Then?

212
00:28:16,720 --> 00:28:19,598
She was supposed to come here one night.
She never arrived.

213
00:28:20,720 --> 00:28:21,835
The killer got her?

214
00:28:22,120 --> 00:28:23,473
How do you know about that?

215
00:28:26,720 --> 00:28:30,952
I thought so.

216
00:28:32,720 --> 00:28:36,633
You must be frozen, child.
She left a coat here.

217
00:28:36,920 --> 00:28:40,708
It's upstairs.
Here, she'll show you were it is.

218
00:29:15,640 --> 00:29:22,352
You are wonderful, Inge.

219
00:29:22,640 --> 00:29:24,756
Stop it, it hurts.

220
00:29:26,320 --> 00:29:31,599
Hold that.

221
00:29:32,400 --> 00:29:34,311
That beats.

222
00:29:37,040 --> 00:29:42,478
They never miss.

223
00:29:42,840 --> 00:29:46,628
This special is supposed to be practically blind.

224
00:29:51,840 --> 00:29:53,910
Be careful, you are in range.

225
00:29:54,320 --> 00:29:55,309
Won't do anythink to me.

226
00:29:59,720 --> 00:30:04,350
In this coat you look like Greta.
She also liked the insects.

227
00:30:04,720 --> 00:30:08,508
But they didn't like her as they like you.

228
00:30:10,320 --> 00:30:11,309
Can you hear the chirping?

229
00:30:12,320 --> 00:30:14,231
This means something special.

230
00:30:16,320 --> 00:30:20,757
It is a mating call.
You are exciting him.

231
00:30:22,920 --> 00:30:23,750
Smell it!

232
00:30:23,920 --> 00:30:25,911
Really?
- Yes, smell.

233
00:30:30,400 --> 00:30:31,719
Sort of sweet.

234
00:30:32,040 --> 00:30:34,110
This substance is secreted by a gland.

235
00:30:34,920 --> 00:30:38,117
It is supposed to attract the female.

236
00:30:39,720 --> 00:30:43,315
You are exciting him and
he is doing his best to excite you.

237
00:30:44,320 --> 00:30:46,959
I don't think so. We only just met.

238
00:30:47,720 --> 00:30:51,554
It isn't the mating season.
I don't understand.

239
00:30:54,320 --> 00:30:56,470
I've never seen anything like that before.

240
00:30:59,720 --> 00:31:02,075
Oh, thanks for everything.

241
00:31:07,720 --> 00:31:09,756
Come by any time.

242
00:31:12,120 --> 00:31:13,155
Night.

243
00:31:14,720 --> 00:31:16,517
To make an old man happy...

244
00:31:16,720 --> 00:31:19,837
...take the cablecar.
It is only a five minutes ride from town.

245
00:31:21,720 --> 00:31:22,914
I don't know. Maybe.

246
00:31:23,720 --> 00:31:26,917
And mind how you go. Without sleepwalking.

247
00:31:27,240 --> 00:31:32,030
If it happens to you again, you must say:
I am sleepwalking, I must wake up.

248
00:31:32,840 --> 00:31:35,798
I am sleepwalking, I must wake up.

249
00:31:37,920 --> 00:31:40,798
I am sleepwalking, I must wake up.

250
00:31:44,120 --> 00:31:49,478
I don't need that. I haven't had an attack for years.

251
00:31:51,320 --> 00:31:52,753
The journey was probably to exhausting.

252
00:31:54,560 --> 00:31:56,391
Or it was caused by the change of air.

253
00:32:00,760 --> 00:32:02,113
Maybe the wind.

254
00:32:03,320 --> 00:32:09,156
That is the foehn, a very strange wind.

255
00:32:09,640 --> 00:32:11,676
It is typical for this area here.

256
00:32:12,240 --> 00:32:14,356
It comes from the south over the Alps.

257
00:32:15,520 --> 00:32:18,318
Such a sudden blast of warm air
causes snow avalanches.

258
00:32:20,120 --> 00:32:24,398
Makes the flowers grow,
the larvae of the insects develop faster.

259
00:32:26,520 --> 00:32:27,919
And many complain about headaches.

260
00:32:29,120 --> 00:32:32,590
When it blows, they say
it drives some people to madness.

261
00:32:33,800 --> 00:32:36,155
This is a rather strange part of the country here.

262
00:32:37,920 --> 00:32:40,593
This Swiss Transylvania.

263
00:32:47,880 --> 00:32:50,917
